Coronavirus: stay up to date
This page will be updated with country-specific information for travellers to Romania. Sign up for email alerts.
See our coronavirus travel advice for guidance on travel during the COVID-19 pandemic, including on cruise ship travel.
Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Romania. The Romanian authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus. These include restrictions on entry from certain countries in response to the global pandemic, and other restrictions on aspects of daily life within Romania. The public health system is already under significant strain. For more information on the measures introduced, see Health
The rules on travel to EU countries will stay the same until 31 December 2020. This page will be updated with country-specific information for travellers to Romania as things change. Sign up for email alerts and view the latest updates for UK nationals travelling to and living in Europe.
Most visits to Romania are trouble-free.
If you’re living in or moving to Romania, read the Living in Romania guide in addition to this travel advice.
Terrorist attacks in Romania can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism.
If you need to contact the emergency services in Romania call 112.
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
The Overseas Business Risk service offers information and advice for British companies operating overseas on how to manage political, economic, and business security-related risks.
You should take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel. For information on the European Health Insurance Card see Health.
